@ifnottex
@node Top
@top Nael — An Emacs major mode for Lean

@samp{nael}, @samp{nael-lsp} and @samp{nael-markdown} are packages extending @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/, GNU Emacs} for editing @uref{https://lean-lang.org, Lean} sources.  Nael is a radically refactored fork of @uref{https://github.com/leanprover-community/lean4-mode, Lean4-Mode} with focus on simplicity, modularity and integration into Emacs' core.  It's still at an early stage of development.

The @samp{nael} package defines the major mode.  In a modular, unobtrusive way, it defines simple and complex abbreviations per @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/emacs/Abbrevs.html, Abbrev} and @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/autotype/, Skeleton} respectively.  It teaches Emacs' built-in @uref{https://microsoft.github.io/language-server-protocol/ Language Server Protocol, LSP} client @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/eglot/, Eglot} about @uref{https://github.com/leanprover/lean4/blob/master/src/Lean/Data/Lsp/Extra.lean, Lean-specific LSP-extensions} and tells @uref{https://www.gnu.org/software/emacs/manual/html_node/emacs/Programming-Language-Doc.html, ElDoc} to display that information, similar to the “@uref{https://github.com/leanprover/vscode-lean4/blob/master/vscode-lean4/manual/manual.md#infoview, info view}” in @uref{https://marketplace.visualstudio.com/items?itemName=leanprover.lean4, vscode-lean} that many are familiar with.

The @samp{nael-lsp} package depends on @uref{https://github.com/emacs-lsp/lsp-mode, lsp-mode}, an external package providing another LSP client, and teaches it about the Lean-specific LSP-extensions.

@end ifnottex

